[1]
Date: Wed 8 Jan 2003
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Ithaca Journal online, Thu 9 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.theithacajournal.com/news/stories/20030109/localregional/738088.html>

USA: Norovirus outbreaks in care facilities across New York state
-----------------------------------------------------------------
The virus responsible for sickening cruise ship passengers appears to have
made its way to the Southern Tier. A Steuben County nursing home and health
care facilities across [New York] state are reporting cases of norovirus
infection, which causes vomiting and diarrhea. It was reported also at the
Waters of Three Rivers nursing home in Gang Mills. The number of cases was
not disclosed.
State and local health officials say they suspect the virus is widespread.
"We're sure it's around, but there's not a routine test for it," said
Melissa Klossner, Chemung County's clinical coordinator of public health.
"People show up at their doctor's with the symptoms and they are done with
it within 24 to 48 hours." Norovirus infections are only reported when the
infected person is admitted to a hospital or is living in a nursing home.
Any sense of how widespread the virus is in the general community is
strictly anecdotal, Klossner said.
The virus was first identified in 1972 after an outbreak of
gastrointestinal illness in Norwalk, Ohio. Other viruses causing similar
symptoms -- nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal cramps, low-grade fever,
and headaches -- have been designated as Norwalk-like viruses. [These
viruses have been grouped together now in the genus _Norovirus_ and
consequently are now referred to as "noroviruses". - Mod.CP] The virus,
spread person to person, is contagious. Those in communal living
situations, such as nursing homes or hospitals, are vulnerable, health
officials said.
The Gang Mills cases, reported on Mon 6 Jan 2003, and others across the
state have prompted the state Health Department to issue alerts to all
hospitals, public health agencies and adult homes in New York. "We're
seeing it all over the state, which is a typical pattern for this time of
year," said state Health Department spokeswoman Kristine Smith. "As of Mon
6 Jan 2003, we have received reports of cases in 39 long-term care
facilities, including 12 in western New York. We also have reports of cases
in one hospital in the Capitol (Albany) region. "Most of reported cases
wouldn't be known because it's generally an illness you don't see a doctor
for. But when the symptoms occur in a health care facility, they have to be
reported to a state health department by law," Smith said.
According to the US Food and Drug Administration, only the common cold is
reported more frequently than gastrointestinal illnesses such as norovirus
infection. It is also estimated that noroviruses are responsible for about
a third (181 000) of all gastrointestinal viral infections occurring in the
United States each year.
