[2]
Date: Thu 9 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Canadian Press, Thu 9 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.canada.com/winnipeg/news/story.asp?id={C1E867E3-8FD9-439F-A590-5FCB29B4F590}>

Canada: more rail passengers with symptoms of norovirus infection
-----------------------------------------------------------------
3 more people who were on the Via Rail train that stopped in Winnipeg on
Tue 7 Jan 2003 after fears it was contaminated with norovirus have fallen
ill. Via Rail confirms that 3 more people who are now in Ontario have
become sick. When the train arrived in Vancouver last weekend, 26 people
were sick with symptoms similar to norovirus infection.
Via employees' union says some workers have also experienced symptoms.
Union spokesman Brad Roy says the illness outbreak may have originated in
the smoking car, often the most crowded on the train.
The train was delayed in Winnipeg for 6 hours on Tuesday while health
officials inspected it. They let the train continue after giving it a clean
bill of health. Transport Canada is investigating, but it will not have any
answers for at least another week.
******
[3]
Date: Fri 10 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Winnipeg Free Press, Fri 10 Jan 2003 [edited]

Canada: current and previous suspected norovirus outbreaks on Via Rail trains
------------------------------------------------
Via Rail said yesterday 3 more people who are now in Ontario are affected
by suspected norovirus infection. 26 passengers were reported ill when the
train arrived in Vancouver from the east last weekend. "The train should
never have left Vancouver," said Brad Roy, health and safety officer for
CAW Local 4002 in Winnipeg. Via Rail officials said they exchanged 9 cars
for new ones in Vancouver and completely sanitized the 2 remaining cars
before the train left the west coast. Just before the train pulled into
Winnipeg Tuesday, one passenger reported feeling ill. The Toronto-bound
train was held up for 6 hours in Winnipeg when some Via staff members
refused to board the train because they feared the train was infected with
norovirus.
Federal health and transport officials met and agreed the train was safe
and it pulled out of the Main Street station Tuesday evening with a full
crew. By the time it arrived in Toronto yesterday, 3 more cases were
reported. The scrub-down of the train in Vancouver obviously wasn't enough
to stop its spread, said Roy, who has worked on an in-house committee
looking at ways of dealing with such outbreaks. He said the vomiting and
diarrhea recently attacked a handful of staff and passengers on the Via
Rail train that runs from Winnipeg to Churchill. Via spokesmen were not
available to confirm that yesterday.
It wouldn't be the first time [norovirus infection] has made life miserable
for Via, said Roy, a senior service attendant with Via. "The first outbreak
was in July 2002," he said. Last summer, up to 17 passengers were affected
by a suspected norovirus outbreak on board a Via Rail train that left
Jasper for Toronto on 5 Jul 2002. Those passengers in turn infected as many
as 100 people they came in contact with after leaving the train, Health
Canada said. Later that month, a similar outbreak affected between 5 and 10
passengers on a Via Rail train that left Toronto for Vancouver on 16 Jul
2002. At the time, federal health officials said the source was not on the
train, but likely brought aboard by an infected passenger. The virus can be
passed from any object touched by an infected person. Epidemiologists have
said it can also be passed when a person vomits in an enclosed area, and
people inhale the air within that area.
Via Rail has said in the past that it's doing everything it can to prevent
the spread of the illness on its trains, but the virus is turning up
everywhere -- not just in Via Rail cars. Norovirus outbreaks have swept
through North America this winter, spreading misery on cruise ships in the
US and forcing Manitoba hospitals to close infected wards.
[byline: Carol Sanders]
