[5]
Date: Fri 10 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-dmail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Latvian News Agency (LETA), Fri 10 Jan 2003 [edited]

Latvia: viral gastroenteritis outbreak in military recruits
-----------------------------------------------------------
72 recruits from the Aluksne Mobile Riflemen Battalion contracted an
intestinal infection yesterday and this morning, and it could possibly be
[caused by] rotavirus. As Uldis Davidovs, the head of the Armed Forces'
Press and Information Department, told LETA, specialists from Military
Medical Center, Disaster Medical Relief Center, and the Public Health
Agency have already departed for Aluksne. [Rotavirus-associated illness is
commoner in younger age groups and this presumptive diagnosis requires
confirmation. - Mod.CP]
Janis Micans, the head of the Military Medical Center, told LETA that the
condition of the conscripts is not serious and local medics may possibly be
able to cope with the situation. The press secretary at the Public Health
Agency, Ieva Lasmane, could not confirm to LETA for the time being whether
there are any cases of infection among civilians.
******
[6]
Date: Mon 13 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Latvian News Agency (LETA), Sun 12 Jan 2003 [edited]

Latvia: gastroenteritis outbreak attributed to faulty water supply
------------------------------------------------------------------
No new cases of an intestinal ailment have been registered today in the
Aluksne Mobile Riflemen Battalion [see above report], where 102 recruits
have been stricken. Nineteen required hospital treatment.
Public Health Agency Press Secretary Ieva Lasmane told LETA that her office
believes that the outbreak of the infection within the ranks could have
been the result of an accident in the water pipeline on Fri 3 Jan 2003. The
first soldiers were stricken on the evening of Thu 9 Jan 2003. [These
circumstances increase the number of potential etiologic agents. - Mod.CP]
