[7]
Date: Sat 11 Jan 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source Houston Chronicle, Sat 11 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/topstory/1732146>

USA: suspected norovirus outbreak at high school in Texas
---------------------------------------------------------
More than 700 students at Cypress Creek High School were absent or sent
home on Friday in what may be an outbreak of norovirus infection, the
illness notorious for plaguing passengers aboard cruise ships.
"It does appear to be an outbreak of norovirus infection," said Rita Obey,
a spokeswoman with the Harris County Public Health Department, which is
investigating the rash of cases. Nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea struck
large numbers of students suddenly, a hallmark of norovirus infection.
Officials in the Cypress-Fairbanks Independent School District in north
west Harris County said 400 of the school's 3200 students were absent on
Thu 9 Jan 2003. By Friday, 646 were absent and 82 more sent home during the
day. The school district canceled Friday night activities at the high
school, but did not call off Monday classes.
More students may fall ill next week because outbreaks tend to occur in
waves, experts warned. "You have several cases and it looks like it goes
away -- then you have several (more) cases," said Kathy Barton, spokeswoman
for Houston Department of Health and Human Services. "We see it a lot,
especially in contained areas such as cruise ships, nursing homes, schools,
areas where you have a captive audience." Washing your hands, covering your
mouth and nose when you cough or sneeze, and not sharing food or drinks are
ways to prevent transmission, Barton said. So far, other area schools
appear free of the virus, Harris County health officials said. County
epidemiologists are looking at possible sources for the outbreak, which is
spread through food, water, or close personal contact.
The noroviruses are among many common microorganisms that can cause
intestinal diseases, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. Norovirus has become a household name in recent months,
sickening more than 1000 passengers and crew members on ships bound for
Hawaii, Alaska, and the Caribbean.
[byline: Leigh Hopper]
******
[8]
Date: Tue 14 Jan 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source Houston Chronicle, Tue14 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/health/1734721>

USA: person to person spread fuelled Texas school outbreak
----------------------------------------------------------
A viral outbreak contributing to more than 700 student absences on Fri 10
2003 (see [7] above) at Cypress Creek High School was spread from person to
person, not through contaminated food or water, school district officials
said on Mon 13 Jan 2003. More than 300 students were absent on Monday from
the 3200 student school in north west Harris County, but officials with
Cypress Fairbanks Independent School District did not know how many of
those were due to the virus infection. The virus, which causes nausea,
vomiting, and diarrhea for 24 to 48 hours, is making its way through
elementary and middle schools that feed into Cypress Creek High School,
district officials said. Those schools have slightly higher-than-usual
student absences, said district spokeswoman Kelli Durham, because the
illness is spreading to younger siblings of infected high school students.
Durham said the schools reported sending vomiting children home on Monday
but did not know how many were ill.
The Harris County health department, which is investigating the outbreak,
said the culprit appears to be a norovirus. [Diagnosis of norovirus
infection is confirmed usually by electron microscopy] of a stool sample.
There is no specific treatment except for comfort measures for symptoms.
Proper handwashing and not sharing food or drinks can prevent transmission.
Rita Obey, a spokeswoman for Harris County Public Health and Environmental
Services, said the timing of the outbreak coincided neatly with students'
return from the winter break. In interviews with students, some said they
began feeling ill before coming to school. The school district cleaned and
sanitized the building over the weekend. Obey said food service areas were
found to be clean.
[byline: Leigh Hopper]
