Date: Wed 15 Jan 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Detroit News, Wed 15 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.detnews.com/2003/health/0301/15/e01-60502.htm>

USA: Metro Detroit area hit by norovirus outbreaks
--------------------------------------------------
A virus grabbing headlines for sickening hundreds of passengers on cruise
ships is hitting Metro Detroit. Emergency room workers at Beaumont
Hospital, Royal Oak were busy over the weekend handling an increase in
norovirus infection cases, Dr Frank McGeorge said. "If I see 20 people in a
day, 4 or 5 might have norovirus infection" he said. "That's twice as bad
as it has ever been." Health officials also are investigating whether 81
people who ate or worked at a Macomb County banquet center just before
Christmas may have contracted the virus, whose symptoms last up to 72
hours. So far, 6 people in that outbreak tested positive for norovirus
infection.
Norovirus gained national attention as hundreds of passengers reported
becoming violently ill while working or vacationing on cruise ships. Since
then, reports of the virus among schoolchildren, nursing-home patients, and
the general population have poured in across the state and the nation. The
US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta predicts
that 23 million people in the United States will contract norovirus
infection this year (about 12.6 per cent of the population). In comparison,
roughly 10 per cent of the US population is expected to contract influenza
virus infection.
There is no commercial norovirus test available to doctors, which compounds
the problem, said Marc-Alain Widdowson, an epidemiologist with CDC. Only
[government laboratories] can test for the virus. But Michigan health
officials do not separate outbreaks by illness unless the federal
government requires the ailment to be tracked. Norovirus infection is not
among those ailments.
Wayne County medical director Donald Lawrenchuk said national studies
suggest that 90 per cent of norovirus cases could be avoided if regular
handwashing was observed.
[byline: Santiago Esparza]
